I am now computing the mgf of a general gaussian, and I added the cgf too.
I added the lemma `mgf_dirac` and removed the unnecessary assumption `hv : v \neq 0`.
@RemyDegenne , friendly ping. Thank you for your attention!
Thanks, @YaelDillies. I applied your suggestions.

This looks good to me. I'll let maintainers decide about https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/19896#discussion_r1900480652

maintainer merge
ðŸš€ Pull request has been placed on the maintainer queue by YaelDillies.
This looks ready to go. Please fix the conflict and ping me for a merge.

Thanks!
bors r+

Pull request successfully merged into master.

Build succeeded!

*And happy new year! ðŸŽ‰*


  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/12588259189/job/35085780733)
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/12588259189/job/35085781257)
Can you also add a lemma (in this PR) for the mgf of a general gaussianReal and also add cgf versions?

To have Omega be a type in any universe:
```suggestion
theorem mgf_gaussian {Î© : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Î©} {Î¼ : Measure Î©}
```

We require spaces before and after `:` . Also you can remove some parentheses and use dot notation for `Measure.map`.
```suggestion
    (X : Î© â†’ â„) (hXm : Measurable X) (hX : Î¼.map X = gaussianReal 0 1) (t : â„) :
```

```suggestion
  mgf X Î¼ t = (Î¼.map X)[fun x => exp (t * x)] := by
```
Same suggestion everywhere else you use map.

I won't insist that you use dot notation everywhere (it's not required by the style guide), but here is an example in case you find it nicer:
```suggestion
      (measurable_exp.comp (continuous_const.mul continuous_id).measurable))
```

You can probably remove the type indication and some parentheses (untested):
```suggestion
  _ = âˆ« x, exp (t * x) * gaussianPDFReal 0 1 x := by
```

```suggestion
    rw [integral_withDensity_eq_integral_smul
      (measurable_gaussianPDFReal 0 1).real_toNNReal]
```

does the following work?
```suggestion
    congr with x
```

```suggestion
  _ = exp (t ^ 2 / 2) * âˆ« x, gaussianPDFReal t 1 x := by
```

You could turn that first step into a lemma:
```lean
lemma mgf_id_map (hX : AEMeasurable X Î¼) : mgf id (Î¼.map X) = mgf X Î¼ := by
  ext x
  rw [mgf, integral_map hX]
  Â· rfl
  Â· exact (measurable_exp.comp (measurable_const_mul _)).aestronglyMeasurable
```
Almost everywhere measurability should be enough? That is, replace hXm by `AEMeasurable X Î¼`.
The hypothesis can then be removed entirely, since a.e.-measurability is a consequence of `hX`. Indeed `Î¼.map X` is defined to be zero if `X` is not a.e.-measurable.

I added a supporting lemma `aemeasurable_of_map`. It seems like it should already exist in mathlib but I could not find it. With it, I can easily remove the hypothesis `hXm`.
I put the new lemma in MeasureSpace. Do you think it belongs there?
`Î¼'` does not seem very useful. You should replace `(hf : Î¼.map f = Î¼') (nezero : Î¼' â‰  0)` with the simpler `(hf : Î¼.map f â‰  0)`.

There is a hierarchy of universes in Lean, and `Type` means a type in universe 1 (see here: https://leanprover.github.io/reference/expressions.html#universes). You should replace it with `Type*`, which means `Type u` for a newly created universe `u`: that makes the statements strictly more general with respect to universes.
Then don't use `MeasureSpace`, but use a `MeasurableSpace` and a measure. This is again for generality. A lemma written for any measure also applies to `volume` in a measure space, but the converse is not true. I know that other parts of this file use `MeasureSpace` and set a bad example, but we should fix that in another PR.
```suggestion
variable {Î© : Type*} {mÎ© : MeasurableSpace Î©} {Î¼ : â„} {v : â„â‰¥0} {X : Î© â†’ â„}
```

All those arguments are already declared in a `variable` line above. Also `X` should be implicit because it can be inferred from `hX`.
```suggestion
lemma mgf_id_map (hX : AEMeasurable X Î¼) : mgf id (Î¼.map X) = mgf X Î¼ := by
```
Add the right version as well? The names that look most like corresponding names elsewhere in the library would be `mgf_const_add` (without the `_left`) and `mgf_add_const`.
The result is also true for `v = 0`, right? The proof will be different and probably needs one more lemma about the mgf of a Dirac.

```suggestion
theorem _root_.AEMeasurable.of_map_ne_zero {f : Î± â†’ Î²} {Î¼ : Measure Î±} (hf : Î¼.map f â‰  0) :
    AEMeasurable f Î¼ := not_imp_comm.1 map_of_not_aemeasurable hf
```

```suggestion
lemma mgf_dirac (hX : p.map X = .dirac Î¼) (t : â„) : mgf X p t = exp (Î¼ * t) := by
```

```suggestion
theorem mgf_gaussianReal (hX : p.map X = gaussianReal Î¼ v) (t : â„) :
```
Same below

```suggestion
theorem mgf_add_const (Î± : â„) : mgf (fun Ï‰ => X Ï‰ + Î±) Î¼ t = mgf X Î¼ t *  exp (t * Î±) := by
  simp only [add_comm, mgf_const_add]
```
to avoid swapping `X` and `Î±` around

Please avoid squeezing terminal simps
```suggestion
    simp [mgf_dirac hX, hv]
```
why? I thought `simp only` is more efficient than `simp`. Why would `simp` ever be preferred over `simp only`?

Because it's more versatile. Every lemma you mention by name is something that could break due to either:
* the lemma being renamed
* the lemma changing statement
I see. What about efficiency though? Isn't `simp` slower than `simp only`?

Actually, not always. In some cases, a simp call is so fast that squeezing it (turning it into a `simp only` with a bunch of lemmas) is slower because of the time it takes to parse the list of lemmas.

Here, it certainly isn't substantially slowing anything down

Think about writing `#min_imports` at the bottom of your file from time to time
```suggestion
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Gaussian.GaussianIntegral
import Mathlib.Probability.Moments
```
Did not know about this command, thanks!

Following the line of sight rule, the main goal in your proof should stay unindented
```suggestion
  calc
  mgf X p t = (p.map X)[fun x => exp (t * x)] := by
    rw [â† mgf_id_map, mgf]
    Â· rfl
    Â· apply AEMeasurable.of_map_ne_zero
      rw [hX]
      exact IsProbabilityMeasure.ne_zero (gaussianReal Î¼ v)
  _ = âˆ« x, exp (t * x) * gaussianPDFReal Î¼ v x := by
    rw [hX, gaussianReal_of_var_ne_zero Î¼ hv, gaussianPDF_def]
    simp only [ENNReal.ofReal]
    rw [integral_withDensity_eq_integral_smul
      (measurable_gaussianPDFReal Î¼ v).real_toNNReal]
    congr with x
    rw [NNReal.smul_def, coe_toNNReal _ (gaussianPDFReal_nonneg Î¼ v x), smul_eq_mul, mul_comm]
  _ = exp (Î¼ * t + v * t ^ 2 / 2)
      * âˆ« x, (âˆš(2 * Ï€ * v))â»Â¹ * exp (-(x - (Î¼ + v * t)) ^ 2 / (2 * v)) := by
    rw [gaussianPDFReal_def, â† integral_mul_left]
    congr with x
    field_simp only [mul_left_comm, â† exp_sub, â† exp_add]
    ring_nf
  _ = exp (Î¼ * t + v * t ^ 2 / 2) * âˆ« x, gaussianPDFReal (Î¼ + v * t) v x := by
    field_simp [gaussianPDFReal_def]
  _ = exp (Î¼ * t + v * t ^ 2 / 2) := by
    rw [integral_gaussianPDFReal_eq_one (Î¼ + v * t) hv, mul_one]
```

You should not be shy to chuck a bunch of stuff into a simp call
```suggestion
    simp [integral_withDensity_eq_integral_smul (measurable_gaussianPDFReal Î¼ v).real_toNNReal, hX,
      gaussianReal_of_var_ne_zero Î¼ hv, gaussianPDF_def, ENNReal.ofReal, NNReal.smul_def, mul_comm]
```
Huh, I thought I tried that and it did not work. Thanks!

The good thing about the new name is that you can use anonymous dot notation:
```suggestion
    Â· refine .of_map_ne_zero ?_
```

```suggestion
      NNReal.smul_def, coe_toNNReal', gaussianPDFReal_nonneg, sup_of_le_left, mul_comm]
```
and some more lemmas might already be simp, like `coe_toNNReal', gaussianPDFReal_nonneg, sup_of_le_left` (actually, the middle one currently isn't, but should be)

```suggestion
    all_goals simp [AEMeasurable.of_map_ne_zero, hX, IsProbabilityMeasure.ne_zero]
```
or
```suggestion
      <;> simp [AEMeasurable.of_map_ne_zero, hX, IsProbabilityMeasure.ne_zero]
```

```suggestion
  Â· exact (measurable_const_mul _).exp.aestronglyMeasurable
```
@YaelDillies , do you know how to condense this to one line?

Here's two tactics:
```lean
  have : IsProbabilityMeasure (p.map X) := by rw [hX]; infer_instance
  rw [â† mgf_id_map (.of_map_ne_zero <| IsProbabilityMeasure.ne_zero _), mgf, hX, integral_dirac,
    mul_comm, id_def]
```
I wonder if there's a msising lemma here though to make this easier.
@YaelDillies , do you know how to do this in a single `simp` call? I tried but did not figure it out.
This is not really in scope for simp. I pushed a golf anyway
If we're protecting these, we should be protecting `csin` etc below too. Can you split this to its own PR, and hit all the similar lemmas at once in this file?
One last request, and then I finally merge this PR: this lemma is not about Gaussians. Could you move it to the Moments file?
